</para><para id="eip-916">Libertarians argue that this state of affairs is accomplished when the role of government and power is kept to a minimum. Although some have argued that libertarianism is a cult or rigid creed, Dr. Davies argues it is not, as there is a great deal of debate within the libertarian tradition.  These internal debates are a sign of intellectual vitality, and are healthy for any intellectual tradition.
</para><section id="eip-100"><title>Discussion Questions</title><para id="eip-440">
<exercise id="texas-exercise">
  <problem id="texas-problem">
    <para id="texas-problem-para">
Which is not a policy you must support to be a consistent libertarian?    
<list id="grocerylist" list-type="enumerated" number-style="upper-alpha"><item>Free markets</item>
  <item>Free trade</item>
  <item>Free movement of people</item>
  <item>Oppose coercive paternalism</item>
  <item>Oppose intervention in foreign affairs</item>
  <item>Free speech</item>
</list></para>
  </problem>
  <solution id="texas-solution">
    <para id="texas-solution-para">
      E. Oppose intervention in foreign affairs
    </para>
  </solution>
</exercise>
